Captain Syrezeaju 22-Nov-19 11:43 PM
By some miracle the gym was empty except from about two people - and upon seeing who had entered, they hastily finished up their last sets and left. Talos wouldnt have kicked them out or anything, but she did appreciate the silence... Running off her anger had always been a strategy she utilised and so she set up the treadmill. Starting out at zero she slowly increased the pace on a programme with an automatically changing incline. Walk, power walk, jog, run; and then a complete sprint. She clocked 2.4k easily and found herself getting more frustrated as she kept going over everything in her head as she ran. 5k, change the pace for a little while. Start doing speed intervals. Might as well make it a 10k... When the treadmill came to a halt upon reaching 10k the display only served to piss her off more - she had taken a minute twenty longer than last time. Immediately bristling with anger at what she viewed as a personal failure - like practically everything she did recently - Talos somehow managed to refrain from kicking the treadmill and tearing it apart. Instead she opted to put her anger to better use and stalked over to the punching bag. Not caring about having left her sparring gloves in her quarters she immediately launched into a workout. To begin with it was a few light punches, a couple of blocks on either side, a couple of half turning kicks... But within a minute the anger had started to flow and she was soon putting the entirety of her strength behind every attack, as if in a desperate attempt to just get rid of this pent up emotion on something, somehow.

Captain Syrezeaju 26-Jul-20 12:38 AM
Things had been entirely calm since the murderer had been arrested and deported off to Security on Earth. There hadn't been any form of crisis to deal with since. It was nice for a moment of calm. A'aehrel's mind was not calm, though. Despite being cleared as a suspect it seemed as if her brain had latched on to the possibilities, Ch'evhalen's words instilling some old sense of fear into her. It was not often that she was fearful - she all but refused to cave to that form of emotion - but it was one still ingrained into her from her past. A complete dread of sentient life had been part of her for years and now it seemed to have grown - a fear of herself. It was a battle of logic. She had been cleared, she had no gaps in her memory... But her thoughts were still plagued by the desire to eliminate the ship's androids. GH-054 had left only to be replaced by the return of 78-KB. A'aehrel had just got rid of one and then the other returned... And with it returned her paranoia. Some sort of subconscious desire for freedom had kicked in too. Logic dictated that, seeing as how she was still suspicious of herself, she should remain in her quarters... But the prospect made her feel physically ill and she had all but refused to return to her quarters for anything longer than an hour at a time. She would rather be anywhere else; inspecting departments, hiding away in her ready room, or even prowling the halls of the recreational deck. At present she had found herself upon that very deck, seemingly having worked on autopilot to get there. By some miracle it was quiet in the gym. Her treadmill was up at a relative speed and despite the physical activity she was still wearing a jumper over standard sports clothing - the heat emulated the feeling of running across the sands of her home planet. If her brain was not going to slow down then perhaps she could outrun it; distraction was a method that would not last, but for now it would have to do. (edited)
Captain Syrezeaju 26-Jul-20 08:51 PM
The Romulan would have been quite content to keep running for hours upon hours. Running was something that had always been natural to her - you were all but trained to run before you could even walk. Chasing after an enemy was the use for it, of course. Running in the opposite direction - away, that was - was just unheard of. With the treadmill set to this pace it wasn't like an outright sprint or anything either. There wasn't any breathlessness, no stupid rushes of adrenaline powering you on. It was leisurely. It was nice. ...Nice until a group of young non-commissioned officers had wandered in to all but invade the free-weights section, that was. They were the typical gym types; loud, brash, and only there to show off and watch themselves in the mirror. A gym was for training, not talking... But they seemed content to do the latter. She tried to ignore it at the start but it was impossible. What a way to ruin her day. It was not long before she slammed stop on the treadmill, forgoing a slow cool-down walk, and slid to the end of the treadmill instead. Neatly she hopped down from the conveyer and headed out of the gym - shooting a glare to the group before she left. Honestly...
